description:
Are Klarna, Shopify, and Duolingo’s AI-first strategies putting profits over people? I have thoughts on their workforce cuts and what it means for employees. 

All thoughts and opinions are my own. 

If you enjoyed this video, please consider supporting the channel by subscribing!

#AIRevolution #AIFirst #TechLayoffs #Duolingo #Klarna

Chapters:
00:00 Intro
00:22 Klarna AI strategy
07:37 Shopify AI strategy
14:13 Duolingo AI strategy
24:20 Duolingo damage control
28:08 Thanks for watching!

comments.text: The Klarna CEO walked back all his AI talk recently. They are now re-hiring humans even for Customer Service jobs which are the jobs that AI should be best at.
comments.author: @zegreatunknown

comments.text: The reality is that there is an enormous amount of hype and not a lot of evidence that AI is all the useful, at least as it exists right now. The people making bold declarations that AI is gonna replace everyone's jobs don't actually understand what goes into most jobs. Recently Marc Andreesen made a comment that AI can replace almost every job, except for his of course. Being an investor requires the "human touch," unlike all other jobs I guess... These people have never actually worked real jobs, and therefore can't imagine why AI can't do them.
comments.author: @cawheeler27

comments.text: Not all. AI is still in their toolbox but they're hiring some people, not everyone, to offset the quality gap.
comments.author: @bapa39

comments.text:
HAAAAA LETS GOOOOOO. I worked there and we were constantly getting handed an unreasonable amount of work because we were going to use AI to replace people's work. Yeah AI is good, but the amount of human oversight still needed is immense.

Working there was the worst year of my life. I thought I developed sleep apnea, but no, it was just stress!

I will say though, the employee count they're saying dropped is almost certainly true. From what I've seen anyways... They are preparing ways to capture the knowledge of employees for when they can let even more go. AI + knowledge graphs
comments.author: @XiaoMoli7844

comments.text: The minute the CEO finds a capable model those new hires will be gone in a flash
comments.author: @dirremoire

comments.text: I use AI coding tool daily for work and while it's not useless, it's a lot less useful than what people are claiming. It does decent code review, writes great git commit messages,  writes some good utility snippets, clean up some code etc. What it doesn't do is write anything more complicated and new. I had to turn code completing off because it kept giving me bad syntax, hallucinated methods and libraries etc. It also doesn't actually seem to be improving especially.
comments.author: @Ruinwyn

comments.text: ​ @Ruinwyn for me that's the biggest gripe with AI: if I have to double check it constantly, how can it be an advantage? I can work with an misaligned physical tool and "hammer it" until it works "right", but why would I prefer that to using a proper aligned tool? I can ask AI for the top 10 accounts in my company portfolio of customers, and their orders from the last 6 months, but if I have to double check it to catch an hallucinated customer or invoice, it's just wasting time, imo. The more complex the data and the output that I want, the bigger my discomfort with the whole thing. That's why my AI usage has been limited to small stuff that I can easily and quickly double check.
comments.author: @holiggan2008

comments.text: I've had better experiences with AI in customer support than with humans, but I won't say that AI is generally better than humans at most desk jobs.
comments.author: @watamatafoyu

comments.text: ​ @cawheeler27  I'm not an expert on AI and it's capabilities. But I will 100% guarantee that most people running AI or developing AI have no damn idea what it's like to do most jobs. This is evident in the fact that many people who are in direct control over most jobs have no damn idea what it's like to do them. That's why we have dumbass rules that hold no bearing in the work done.
comments.author: @Introverted100

comments.text: To be fair, CEOs have a legal, fiduciary, responsibility to maximize shareholder value. So if a job  could be done more cheaply with AI, they pretty much have to do it, otherwise they get sued big-time. That's just how capitalism works.
comments.author: @dirremoire

comments.text: Makes sense. The automation needs a lot of initial guidance but it shouldn't take long for the majority use cases to be nailed down.
comments.author: @tenou213

comments.text:
Typical MBA, "we will fire all these people and make a huge profit for our shareholders".

"Ooooops, things dont work, let's hire a bunch of people. This is completely unrelated to firing a bunch of people earlier."
comments.author: @BillClinton228

comments.text:
Because they realized ai sucks big time. It simply does, it sucks. Ai is not even ai, it’s chatbots. They are not intelligent, there is no such thing as agents, there is ZERO reliability and accountability, no guarantees, no nothing, it’s all angel dust. So, when the “ai” fucks the new product launch, or annoys the fuck out of a customer, or simply malfunctions, the blame goes on to the ceo. There is no project manager anymore, there is just garbage on the other side.

If this person thought of doing what he was about to do in the first place, I’m done with him and his company.

Ai has become a surprisingly good tool to discern garbage people vs descent folks.
comments.author: @Joris-KarlHuysmans

comments.text: @dirremoire  exactly. It’s the person, not the technology.
comments.author: @Joris-KarlHuysmans

comments.text: Just read that. I've been saying it for a few years now (especially for software engineers.) It is a great tool, and should be used as such, not a black box that runs everything.

comments.text: Speaking as a customer, I do not want to talk to a robot. I want to talk to a human. I never liked talking to an automated caller in the past and I would not like to talk to an advanced version of "press 1, press 2, press 1, press 3, goodbye".

comments.text: ​ @cawheeler27 That is actually pretty funny. I would say investor is one of the jobs where the human touch is just as much in the way to make good decisions. A lot of investment decisions are made based on gut feeling rather than raw data and statistics. Our biases makes us take bad decisions, while an AI could analyze all the data without any emotional attachment and probably make a better decision.
